            <div type="figure" subtype="drawing">
                <figure>
                    <figDesc>Pen and ink, approx. ? &#x00D7; ? cm (image only). The editors of the <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="library_edition_note.html">Library Edition</ref> 
                        describe the image as a &#x201C;sketch of the <geogName corresp="#RHINE">Rhine</geogName> with the fortress high on the hill, and the town below&#x201D; 
                        (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.html#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:355; a facsimile of the drawing and verse is bound opposite this page). 
                        <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> based his vignette on an engraving, &#x201C;<geogName corresp="#EHRENBREITSTEIN">Ehrenbreitstein</geogName>,&#x201D; by <persName corresp="#RW">Robert Wallis</persName> after <persName corresp="#JMWT">J. M. W. Turner</persName>, 
                        published in the <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#KEEPSAKE1833"><hi rend="italic">Keepsake for MDCCCXXXIII</hi></ref> (p. 84 opp.) 
                        (see <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.html#HEWISONETALRUSKINTURNERPRB">Hewison, Warrell, and Wildman, <hi rend="italic">Ruskin, Turner, and the Pre&#x2010;Raphaelites</hi></ref>, 45). 
                        <persName corresp="#JMWT">Turner</persName>&#x02BC;s engraving is not a vignette, but a full&#x2010;page, broadside rectangle; 
                        so to reframe the image, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> may have drawn on a vignette engraving, &#x201C;<geogName corresp="#DRACHENFELS">Drachenfels</geogName>&#x201D;, after <persName corresp="#DRP">David Roberts</persName>, 
                        published in <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#BULWERLYTTONPILGRIMS"><title type="book" corresp="#BULWERLYTTONPILGRIMS"><hi rend="italic">The Pilgrims of the Rhine</hi></title></ref> (<date when="1834">1834</date>) 
                        by <persName corresp="#EBL">Edward Bulwer&#x2010;Lytton</persName> (p. 100). <persName corresp="#DRP">Roberts</persName>&#x02BC;s <geogName corresp="#RHINE">Rhine</geogName> view is suggestive of <persName corresp="#JMWT">Turner</persName>&#x02BC;s scene, but contained in an oval vignette.
